# **6. Why does this work?**

The most recently opened bracket must always be closed first.

A **Stack** follows exactly this behavior:

* **Push** every opening bracket.
* **Pop** when a matching closing bracket is found.

If a mismatch occurs or the stack is empty when a closing bracket appears, the string is invalid.

If the stack is empty at the end, every opening bracket has been matched correctly.

---

# **7. Java Code**

```java
class Solution {

    public boolean isValid(String s) {

        Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();

        for (char ch : s.toCharArray()) {

            if (ch == '(' || ch == '{' || ch == '[') {
                stack.push(ch);
            } else {

                if (stack.isEmpty())
                    return false;

                char top = stack.pop();

                if ((ch == ')' && top != '(') ||
                    (ch == '}' && top != '{') ||
                    (ch == ']' && top != '['))
                    return false;
            }
        }

        return stack.isEmpty();
    }
}
```

---

# **8. Time Complexity**

**O(n)**

* `n` = length of the string.
* Each character is pushed and popped at most once.

---

# **9. Space Complexity**

**O(n)**

In the worst case (all opening brackets), all characters are stored in the stack.

---

# **10. Important Interview Note**

A **Stack** is the ideal data structure for problems involving **matching pairs** and **nested structures**.

Remember:

* Opening brackets → **Push**
* Closing brackets → **Pop and Compare**

Also, always check if the stack is empty before popping to avoid errors.

---

# **11. One-line Note for Interviews**

**Use a stack to store opening brackets. For every closing bracket, pop the top element and check if it matches. If all brackets match and the stack is empty at the end, the string is valid.** 🚀
